🚨 Detecting Device Code Phishing with KQL (Microsoft Sentinel / Defender)

Device code phishing is becoming a popular technique where attackers trick users into authenticating via Microsoft’s device login flow — and then silently register a device under the attacker’s control.

Here’s a simple detection approach 👇

🔍 What we’re looking for:
• A user clicks a phishing link pointing to Microsoft device login
• The same user registers a device shortly after

💡 Detection logic (KQL):

CloudAppEvents
| where Timestamp > ago(1h)
| where AccountDisplayName == "Device Registration Service"
| extend ID = extract("Device_(.*)", 1, tostring(RawEventData.ObjectId))
| join IdentityInfo on $left.ID == $right.AccountObjectId
| join (
    UrlClickEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(1h)
    | where Workload == "Email"
    | where ActionType in ("ClickAllowed", "UrlScanInProgress", "UrlErrorPage")
        or IsClickedThrough != "0"
    | where UrlChain has_any (
        "microsoft.com/devicelogin",
        "login.microsoftonline.com/common/oauth2/deviceauth"
    )
    | distinct AccountUpn
) on AccountUpn

⚠️ Important Insight:
This detection correlates activity within the same time window — but it does not guarantee sequence (i.e., click → registration). Fine-tuning with tighter time correlation or session IDs can improve accuracy.

🎯 Why it matters:
This technique bypasses traditional phishing defenses because users are interacting with legitimate Microsoft endpoints.

🛡️ Defensive tips:
• Monitor unusual device registrations
• Apply Conditional Access policies
• Educate users about device login prompts
• Investigate suspicious URL click patterns
